      Special Tribunal for Ukraine 
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/zelensky-russia-accountability-statement.jpg" alt="Zelensky said that every war criminal must know there will be justice, and that includes Russia" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>
          Zelensky said that every war criminal must know there will be justice, and that includes Russia. Credits: AP Photo/Pascal Bastien</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       President Zelenskyy <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-jun-25-spotlight-h1-1-signed-an-agreement?source=website" target="_blank">signed an agreement</a> with the Council of Europe to set up a special tribunal. This tribunal will prosecute top Russian officials for the “crime of aggression” linked to the 2022 invasion. This move fills a gap left by the International Criminal Court, which lacks jurisdiction over cases of aggression.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
     Council of Europe Secretary General Alain Berset stated that the next step is to gain broader international support. The tribunal could begin operations as early as 2026. This marks the first of its kind under the Council of Europe’s framework.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       Meanwhile, as the EU summit gets underway in Brussels, Ukraine will be a key focal point of discussion. Baltic leaders, Lithuanian President Gitanas Nauseda and Estonian PM Kristen Michal, <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-jun-25-spotlight-h1-2-are-renewing-calls?source=website" target="_blank">are renewing calls</a> for Ukraine’s EU membership.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;"> Nauseda urged opening negotiations shortly, setting a target for Ukraine to join by 2030. Michal emphasized that Ukraine’s accession would strengthen pressure on Russia. </p>
