          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
    Korea’s nuclear landscape
       </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
        Summary: North and South Korea pursue nuclear capabilities amid a traumatic legacy. </strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
           The Korean Peninsula's link to nuclear weapons shows a clear gap between military goals and human suffering. North and South Korea have <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-jun-25-analysis-h1-5-both-pursued-nuclear-capabilities?source=website" target="_blank">both pursued nuclear capabilities</a>, whether through development or hosting foreign armaments. Meanwhile, the trauma of Korean atomic bomb victims remains a painful part of history. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Several Koreans were among the victims of the Hiroshima-Nagasaki atomic bombing. They were brought to Japan as forced laborers during the colonial era to support its war efforts. At 11:02 am on Aug 9, 1945, the US dropped the “Fat Man,” a 20-kiloton plutonium bomb, and devastated many lives. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          According to estimates by the Association of A-bomb Victims of South Korea, the combined number of Korean victims ranges between 70,000 and 100,000 Koreans, with roughly 40,000 to 50,000 fatalities. Unlike Japanese survivors, Korean Hibakusha faced neglect, discrimination, and often lacked clinical care or recognition. Some of them who returned to Korea faced social isolation and were expected to suppress their trauma.
          </p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Currently, approximately 1,600 Korean survivors remain, living quietly in places such as Hapcheon, South Korea. They even have a small museum that was opened in 2017 to honor their stories, which exposes the lasting damage caused by nuclear weapons across generations. As international awareness grows, Korean and Japanese survivors are uniting and pushing for nuclear disarmament instead of retaliation. 
          </p>
        </mj-text>
